<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920305-0147</DOCNO><DOCID>920305-0147.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor:   Too Many Fat Generals   Can Feed a Revolution</HL><DATE>03/05/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15</SO><RE>SOUTH AMERICA (SM)VENEZUELA (VE)</RE><LP>   In regard to your Feb. 7 Americas column, &quot;Seeds ofVenezuelan Revolt Found in Statist System&quot; by Carlos Ball:The author's points are well made, but he does not addressthe primary reasons behind the attempted coup or thesingle-minded focus on terminating President Carlos AndresPerez . . . which almost succeeded.   For the past three decades Venezuela has kept its armedforces in the barracks by fattening its generals, with notrickledown to the real muscle -- the colonels and captains.Reading about President Perez is very hard for a soldier toswallow with only rice and beans on his plate -- his only dueon a captain's wage. It is an open secret that no project canproceed without the president's nod, conveyed through one ofhis personal aides.</LP><TEXT>   We hear that the coup was more than a year in the planningand fueled by rumors of presidential greed -- a second timearound. Remember what happened to Ferdinand Marcos? Thechapter is not closed.   Pravin Banker   Editor in Chief   LDC Bond Watch   New York</TEXT></DOC>